Subj:	hyaluronan in diatom trails?

I've hypothesized that the diatom trail consists of a material that is
hydrophobic within the raphe, and that hydration provides the energy for
motility, turning this stuff into a hydrophilic form that comes out of the
raphe. See:
 
Gordon, R. & R. W. Drum (1970).  A capillarity mechanism for diatom gliding
locomotion.  Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. USA 67, 338-344.
 
Gordon, R. (1987). A retaliatory role for algal projectiles, with
implications for the mechanochemistry of diatom gliding motility. J. Theor.
Biol. 126, 419-436.
 
John Scott has discovered that hyaluronan changes from hydrophobic to
hydrophilic on hydration:
 
Scott, J.E. (1989a). Secondary structures in hyaluronan solutions: chemical
and biological implications. Ciba Found. Symp.  143, 6-20, 281-285.
 
Have any of you got evidence for hyaluronan in diatom trails or other
secretions?
 
Yours, -Dick Gordon
 
